04478nam a22006495i 9780691225739DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20222021nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021944468  a97806912257397 a10.1515/97806912257392doi  a(DE-B1597)589308  a(OCoLC)1302163393  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aMAT0220002bisacsh1 aKriz, Daniel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSupersingular p-adic L-functions, Maass-Shimura Operators and Waldspurger Formulas :b(AMS-212) /cDaniel Kriz. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnnals of Mathematics Studies ;v40500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Preliminaries: Generalities -- t3 Preliminaries: Geometry of the infinite-level modular curve -- t4 The fundamental de Rham periods -- t5 The p-adic Maass-Shimura operator -- t6 P-adic analysis of the p-adic Maass-Shimura operators -- t7 Bounding periods at supersingular CM points -- t8 Supersingular Rankin-Selberg p-adic L-functions -- t9 The p-adic Waldspurger formula -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA groundbreaking contribution to number theory that unifies classical and modern resultsThis book develops a new theory of p-adic modular forms on modular curves, extending Katz's classical theory to the supersingular locus. The main novelty is to move to infinite level and extend coefficients to period sheaves coming from relative p-adic Hodge theory. This makes it possible to trivialize the Hodge bundle on the infinite-level modular curve by a "canonical differential" that restricts to the Katz canonical differential on the ordinary Igusa tower. Daniel Kriz defines generalized p-adic modular forms as sections of relative period sheaves transforming under the Galois group of the modular curve by weight characters. He introduces the fundamental de Rham period, measuring the position of the Hodge filtration in relative de Rham cohomology. This period can be viewed as a counterpart to Scholze's Hodge-Tate period, and the two periods satisfy a Legendre-type relation. Using these periods, Kriz constructs splittings of the Hodge filtration on the infinite-level modular curve, defining p-adic Maass-Shimura operators that act on generalized p-adic modular forms as weight-raising operators. Through analysis of the p-adic properties of these Maass-Shimura operators, he constructs new p-adic L-functions interpolating central critical Rankin-Selberg L-values, giving analogues of the p-adic L-functions of Katz, Bertolini-Darmon-Prasanna, and Liu-Zhang-Zhang for imaginary quadratic fields in which p is inert or ramified. These p-adic L-functions yield new p-adic Waldspurger formulas at special values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aL-functions. 0aNumber theory. 0ap-adic analysis. 7aMATHEMATICS / Number Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073912140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691225739?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780691225739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780691225739/original  a978-3-11-073912-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_MTPY  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MTPY  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK